{
  "DNA Replication and Repair": "",
  "This lesson covers the fundamental measures of center used to analyze and summarize data sets. You'll learn how to calculate and apply the mean, median, and mode, and understand when each is most appropriate.": "",
  "What is 'semiconservative replication'?": "",
  "Semiconservative replication describes how each parental DNA strand serves as a template for a new complementary strand, so each daughter molecule retains ('conserves') one of the original strands paired with one new strand.": "",
  "What is an 'origin of replication'?": "",
  "An origin of replication (ORI) is a specific sequence in the DNA where proteins bind to initiate the unwinding of the helix and the assembly of the replication machinery. Eukaryotic chromosomes have multiple origins to speed replication.": "",
  "What is 'DNA ligase'?": "",
  "DNA ligase joins breaks (nicks) in the DNA backbone by catalyzing the formation of a phosphodiester bond between the 3'-OH of one fragment and the 5'-phosphate of the adjacent fragment. It is essential for joining Okazaki fragments and completing DNA repair.": "",
  "What is 'nucleotide excision repair'?": "",
  "Nucleotide excision repair (NER) recognizes bulky DNA distortions (such as thymine dimers caused by UV light), cuts the damaged strand on both sides of the lesion, removes the segment, and uses DNA polymerase and ligase to fill the gap.": "",
  "What is a 'telomere'?": "",
  "Telomeres are repetitive sequences (TTAGGG in humans) at chromosome ends that form protective caps. They prevent chromosome deterioration and end-to-end fusion, and they shorten with each cell division unless maintained by telomerase.": "",
  "What is 'helicase'?": "",
  "Helicase is an ATP-dependent enzyme that travels along the DNA double helix, breaking the hydrogen bonds between base pairs and separating the two strands to create single-stranded templates at the replication fork.": "",
  "Lynch syndrome (hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer) is caused by inherited mutations in mismatch repair genes. Patients with this condition develop colorectal cancer at a much younger age than the general population. What is the molecular basis for this increased cancer risk?": "",
  "Defective mismatch repair means that base-pairing errors introduced during DNA replication are not corrected, leading to a 'mutator phenotype' with a dramatically elevated mutation rate. This accelerates the accumulation of mutations in oncogenes and tumor suppressors.": "",
  "A geneticist studies a patient with xeroderma pigmentosum (XP), a condition in which the nucleotide excision repair pathway is defective. The patient develops severe sunburns and skin cancers with minimal UV exposure. Why is this repair pathway so critical for protection against UV damage?": "",
  "UV radiation causes adjacent thymine bases to form covalent dimers, which distort the DNA helix and block replication and transcription. Nucleotide excision repair specifically recognizes and removes these bulky lesions. Without NER, thymine dimers persist and cause mutations.": "",
  "Eukaryotic chromosomes have multiple origins of replication, while the typical bacterial chromosome has just one. Why is having multiple origins advantageous for eukaryotes?": "",
  "Human cells have approximately 3 billion base pairs to replicate. With multiple origins of replication (tens of thousands), many replication forks operate simultaneously across each chromosome, allowing the entire genome to be copied within hours.": ""
}